{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_havarti_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868983/1927032901/0636.xml":{"full_text":"BANK TRANSACTIONS\nMonday, March 28, 1927\n$22,990,910\nAll banks reported.\nGeneral Motors Spurts to Further Gains on Exchange\nEARLY DEALS\nFIND U. S. STEEL\nSHARES AHEAD\nRail Stocks Again\nAdvance in\nVolume.\nNEW YORK General Motors\nspurted to another new record for\nthe present shares in early dealings\non the stock market today at 182%,\nup Vi, imparting strength to\nthe rest of the list. U. S. Steel\nfirmed up to 165%. Attchison,\nBaldwin, Delaware Hudson and\nother leading issues were in urgent\ndemand at higher prices.\nRailroad shares again led in vol\nume and prices advanced with\nnearly all issues in the group show\nig considerably better prices. Dela\nware Hudson advanced 1% to\n196%; Atchison to 180; New York\nCentral, to 146; New Haven,\nto 51; C. 0., to 165, and Read\ning to 110%.\nWillys-Overland was fairly active\nin the automobile division, rising\nto 22%, up from the previous\nclose. Hudson eased off to 69%,\nand Mack Truck gained to 104%.\nSpecialties also were well taken\nincluding Matheison Alkali, which\nrose to 107%. Baldwin spurted\n2% to 184% on the initial sale but\nlater eased off to 184.\nU. S. Steel, 165%, up General\nMotors, 182%, up Reading,\n110%, up Hudson, 69%, up\nNorthern Pacific, 86%; Mack\nTiuck, 104%, up Dupont, 216%\nM. Y. Central, 146%; Baldwin,\n184%, up 2% 5 Pan-American Petro\nleum B, 64%; Standard Oil of New\nJirsey, 37%; U. S. Rubbert, 62%,\nup 5 Pennsylvania, 59%; Willys-\nOverland, 22, up Westinghouse,\n76%; B. 0., 115%, up C.\n0., 165%, up Atchison, 178%,\nup\nJARDINE TAKES\nHAND IN QUIZ\nOF GRAIN CO.\nWASHINGTON Secretary of\nAgriculture W. M. Jardine accuses\nthe Chicago Board of Trade of re\nfusing the government access to\nrecords involving the Armour Grain\nCo. in a newly disclosed scandal\nwhich caused the secretary to cite\nthe grain company to show cause\nwhy it should not be denied trading\nprivileges, it became known yester\nday.\nSecretary Jardine, it was learned,\ndirected L. A. Fitz, grain exchange\nsupervisor at Chicago, to co-oper\nate with the state legislative com\nmittee headed by Representative\nThomas Curran, in exposing con\nditions on the Chicago Board of\nTrade.\nThe board notified Secretary\nJardine that it would not permit\ngovernmental inspection of the rec\nords of its weighing department\n\u201cunless required to do so by law\u201d or\nunless \u201cit were clearly apparent\nthat it were urgently necessary for\nthe public good,\u201d Mr. Jardine de\nclared in a letter written to Atty.\nBenjamin F. Goldstein, special\ncounsel for the Illinois legislative\ncommittee.\nGAS NET LT.\nCHICAGO\u2014The Oklahoma Gas\nElectric Co., one of the properties\nunder Byllesby management, and a\nsubsidiary of Standard Gas Elec\ntric recorded a substantial gain m\nearnings last year, with gross 21.27\nper cent and net 25.02 per cent\nabove 1925. Gross earnings amount\ned to .$10,888,761, compared with\n$8,978,554 the preceding year, while\nnet was $3,987,660. against $3,189.-\n598. After payment of interest and\npreferred dividends there was a bal\nance for retirement reserves, com\nmon dividends, amortization and\nsurplus, of $1,109,794 in 1926, com\nparing with $692,757 in 1925.\nNew York Cotton\nNEW YORK\u2014Cotton opened four to\neight pointe higher. May 14.17: Jul y\n14.37; October 14.58; January 14,<6.\nMilwaukee Livestock\nHOGS \u2014Receipts, 500; 25@30c lower.\nPrime heavy and butchers,\n200 lbs- up f10.i5@11.55\nPrime heavy and butchers,\n200-240 lbs* 11.50 w 11.60\nFair to good lights H'o-SUnn\nFresh light lights, 130-160.. 11.2a@12.00\nFair to select packers 9.50 10.1 a\nPigs and light lights 10.00@11.25\n9. <o\nGovernment throwouts I.oo@ 8.00\nBoars I.oo@ 7.00\nCATTLE\u2014 Receipts. 300; steady.\nSteers, good to choice..... 9.00@11.00\nMedium to good B.oo@ 9.00\nFair to medium 7.25 8.50\nCommon 5.00@ 7.00\nHeifers, goojl to choice..... 7.00@ 8.00\nMedium to good 6.00@ 6.75\nFair to medium 5.50@ 6.00\nCommon to fair 4.50 5.00\nown, good to choice 6.00 7.50\nM.'diu mto good 4.75@ 5.25\nKiir to medium 5.25@ 5.75\nCutters 4.65ffS 5.00\nCanners 4.25@ 4.50\nButchers\u2019 bulls 6.50@ 6.75\nBologna bulls 5.50@ 6.50\nMilkars and springers, good\nto choice (common sell\nfor beef) 60.00@85.00\nCALVES\u2014Receipts, 1,000; steady.\nGood to choice, 100 lbs. up.? 9.75@10.00\nFair to good 9.00@ 9.50\nThrowouts 5.00@ 5.50\nSHEEP \u2014Receipts. 100; 25@50c higher.\nGood to choice ewes and\nwether lambs $14.50@16.00\nMedium to good 12.50@13.50\nHeavy bulfs iambs 11.00@12.50\nLight ewes 7.50 9.00\nCull ewes 1.00 4.00\nBucks 3.00@ 5.00\nifr \u2014t\u2014\u25a0 IMI I Wil HI. O-T O-C*\nj Gainford Is Head\nOf British Group\\\nI* 'j/' 7 JF\nLord Gainford, who has\nlong held positions of trust id\nthe British government, was\nnominated as president-elect\nof the Federation of British\nIndiistries, succeeding Sir\nMax Muspratt.\nAmerican Output\nEfficiency Wins\nPraise of British\nLONDON\u2014WhiIe the British in\ndustrial commission which toured\nthe United States last fall was im\npressed with efficiency of produc\ntion in American manufacturing\ncidcles, it believes \u201cAmerica has not\nyet solved many problems of post\nwar industry, and many sections of\ntrade are still gravely depressed,\u201d\naccording to the commission\u2019s report\npublished today.\nAlthough wages in the United\nStates are higher than in Great\nBritain, the old age pensions and\nunemployment insurance in force\non this side of the Atlantic more\nthan offset the larger remuneration\nfor workers, the report claims.\nBALDWIN HEAD\nLIKES FUTURE\nNEW YORK\u2014Samuel M. Vau\nclain, president of the Baldwin Lo\ncomotive works, is optimistic re\ngarding the outlook for that com\npany, announcing yesterday that\nthe current volume of business has\nmade it necessary to step produc\ntion up from 40 to 50 per cent of\ncapacity. \u201cAnd I look for further\nimprovement in production around\nthe first of April,\u201d Mr. Vauclain\nadded.\nGerman Shipping\nLines Have Big Year\nBERLIN\u2014The best business con\nditions since the war were reported\nby the largest German shipping\ncompanies, the North German Lloyd\nand the Hamburg-American line, at\nstockholders\u2019 meetings today.\nThe meetings approved payment\nof 6 per cent dividends for 1927.\nThe Hamburg-American stock\nholders also approved a $7,500,000\nincrease in carkalization by the\nsale of new stock.\nLT. S. GETS WOOD.\nWASHINGTON The United\nStates imported 499,000 feet of cab\ninet woods in the leg, valued at\n$27,825, and 2,107,000 feet of sawed\nhardwood lumber, valued at $214,-\n187, from Tokio, Japan, during 1926,\nsays a report from Consul General\nEdwin L. Neville, Tokio, made pub\nlie by the commerce department.\nMilwaukee Produce Prices\u2014Corrected Daily\nN DAIRY MARKETS.\nButter\u2014Creamery, fresh,' extras, tubs,\nSO^c; extra firsts, 49@50c; centralized,\n88 to 89 score, 47@48c; ladles, 38@40c;\npacking stock No. I, 30 33cT off-stock,\n15\u00ae 20c.\nCheese American, full cream, twins,\n22&@23c; daisies, single, 23@23%c;\ndouble, 23@23%c; Young Americas, 23@\n2314 c; longhorns, 23\u20194 @24c; squares,\n23\u20194 @24c. 5-lb. loaves \u2014American, 31\n33c; pimento, 34@36c; brick, 32@34c;\nSwiss, 88@41c. Special makes \u2014Brick,\nfancy. 2214 @23c; Hmburger, 25@26c;\nSwiss, block, 26@29c; loaf, 30@36c; im\nported, Swiss, 42@45c.\nEggs\u2014Fresh-gathered firsts, standard\ncases included, 231i@23%c; ordinary\nfirsts, shippers' cases included, 22@22%c;\ndirties, candled, 20%@21c; seconds,\nchecks, candled, 20 @20\u201940.\nMEATS AND POULTRY.\nPigeons Old flyers, live, per doz.,\n$1 25; dead, 95c; squabs, live, per doz.,\n$1.50@2.00; dressed, fat. $2.00@2.50;\nthin, poorly dressed, t1.00@1.50.\nPoultry\u2014Live\u2014Fowls. 3 to 5 lbs., 28c;\nunder 3 lbs., 25c; roosters, 20c; spring\ners, fancy, soft meats, 33c; stags, 25c;\nleghorns, 25c; turkeys, plump, 30c;\nducks, 32c; geese, 16c; Guinea hens, per\ndozen, old. $5.00; young. $6.00.\nVeal\u2014Calves, 50 to 60 lbs., fair kid\nneys. 10@llc; 60 to 70 lbs., choice,\nmeaty. ll@12c; 70 to 80 lbs., good kid\nneys, 12 13c; 80 to 90 lbs., choice, 13\n15c; 90 to 110 lbs., fancy, bright, 15@\n16c; evtra'fancy, 16@17c; thin, bony,\npoor kidneys, poorly dressed or off\nstock. 80 to 175 lbs., as to quality and\ncondit\u2019oy. 9@llc,\nHides-\u2014Cait, green, 17c; cured, 18c;\nkips, green, 12c; cured, 13c; cow, green,\n7c; cured. 8c; bull, green, sc; cured, 6c;\ndeacons, green, each. 60c; slunk, green,\neach 25c; horse No. 1. green, each, $3.50;\ndo, No. 2 green, each, $2.25; pelts, green,\neach, sCc@sl.so.\nFRUITS.\nApples Michigan or Wisconsin, per\nbushel, 75c@51.25; barrels. $3.00@4.00;\nWestern, boxes, Jonathans, $2.50@2.75;\nDelicious. $3.50@3.75; Snitzenberg. $2.50\n2.75; Wine Saps, $2.50@2.75; barrels.\nNew York Greenings. $5.00@5.50. t\nBananas\u2014Per 100 lbs., $6.00 @7.00.\nGrapes\u2014Almerlas, 20 lb. boxes, SIO.OO\n@ll.OO.\nGrape Fruit\u2014Florida, per box, as to\nThe Leader Financial Page\nTWELVE\nC^HOMEJj\u00abK\nExperiments by experts have\nshown that all peas, even the\ndwarfed varieties, do best with\nsome support. Even the Little\nMarvel, one of the shortest, will give\nbetter crops with the support of a\nnarrow length of chicken wire or\nilght brush, or even strings stretched\nbetween stout stakes. The support\nis not necessary, but the peas will\nbe of finer quality and more freely\nproduced, the experts tell us if the\nvines are held erect, which is their\nnatural position if they can find\nanything to which to cling.\nThe narrow width chicken wire\ncan be rolled up after the peas are\ndone and can be stored for another\nseason. To rid it of the dead vines\nthey can be burned off quickly if\nallowed to become thoroughly dry.\nSome progress is now being made\nin the earliest of all peas, the\nsmooth seeded sorts, which are\nhardier than the better quality\nwrinkled sorts and can be planted\nearlier with certainty of a crop.\nThey are a valuable garden pea.\nbecause of their earliness. They\ncan be planted as\" soon as the\nground can be worked and are one\nof the first garden crops to go in.\nFormerly the old Alaska and\nKlondyke were the mainstays, iden-\nRAIL SHARES\nMOVE AHEAD\nON GOOD NETS\nBuying of railroad shares yester\nday, which was stiriiulated by the\ngenerally favorable earnings state\nments, resulted in the highest rail\nroad stock market average in 18\nyears. The average of 20 rails was\n130.01, representing an advance of\n1.69 over Saturday\u2019s quotations and\ncomparing with the best previous\naverage of 134.4 Gin 1909. This\nalso represented a gain of 24.86\npoints over a year ago when the\naverage was 105.15.\n20 Per Cent Jump Seen.\nAlthough the earnings statements\nfor February showed an irregular\ntrend, the net railway operating in\ncome of the carriers thus far re\nported was approximately 20 per\ncent in excess of February last year.\nThis was largely due to the splen\ndid showing of the Atchison, Penn\nsylvania and the coal carriers. It\nis not considered likely, however,\nthat this rate of increase will be\nreflected in the final returns.\nThe report of the Atchison, To\npeka Santa Fe railway reflect\ned the large volume of oil \"and wheat\ntraffic as compared with last year.\nIts gross revenues amounted to $19,-\n448,276, an increase of $2,803,217\nover last year. As a result of heav\nier expenses the net railway op\nerating income showed an increase\nof $987,300.\nThe Pennsylvania had a net rail\nway operating income of $7,142,845,\nan increase of more than 50 per\ncent as compared with last year.\nAll the carriers operating in the\nanthracite district reported substan\ntial increases, due principally to the\nfact that earnings last year were\nseriously affected on account of the\nstrike.\nThe earnings statements of the\ncarriers operating in the southern\nregion reflect the business recession\nin that region. The Louisville\nNashville and the Atlantic Coast\nLine reported declines In net rail\nway operating income of $362,899\nand $911,941 respectively.\nThe Southern railway had a net\nrailway operating income of $2,759,-\n460, a decrease of $350,953 as com\npared with last year.\nsize and quality, $3.50@4.50.\nLemons \u2014California, per box, $4.50\n5.00.\nLimes \u2014Imported, 100, $2.00@2.25.\nOranges California, new Navels, per\nbox. as to size and quality, $5.00@6.50;\nFlorida, $4.50@5.00; Indian Rivers, $5.50\n@6.00.\nTangerines\u2014Florida, \u20194 boxes, $2.50@\n2.75.\nPears\u2014Western, boxes, Winter Welles,\n$4.00@4.60.\nPineapples\u2014Cuban, crate, $7.00 @3.00.\nBERRIES.\nCranberries Capa Cods, boxent $3.00\n@4.00.\nStrawberries\u2014Louisiana, 24-pint cases,\n$5.25@5.75.\nAsparagus\u2014California, crate, 12 bchs.,\n$6.00@9.00.\nAvaeadoes\u2014Caltf., doz., $4,00 @IO,OO.\nBeets Home-grown, bushels, 50@\n60c; new, Texas, bushels, $1.75@2.00.\nCabbage Home-grown, bushel, 40\n50c; barrels, $1.25@1.50; Holland seed,\nper ton, $10.00@12.00; new, Texas, crate,\n$3.00@3.25; bulk, bbls., $2.75@3.00.\nCarrots Home-grown, bushels, 65@\n75c; new, Texas, bushels, $2.00@2.25.\nCauliflower\u2014California, crate, ?2.75@\n3.25.\nCelery\u2014California, crate, $6.00 @7.00;\nFlorida, $3.25@3.50.\nCelery Root\u2014Home-grown, doz.. as to\nsize, 25@50c.\nCucumbers\u2014Hot house, boxes, 2 doz.,\n$5.00@5.50; home-grown, doz., $2.00@\n2.50.\nEgg Plant\u2014Florida, crate, SB.OO @9.00.\nGarlic\u2014California, per lb., 6@Bc.\nGreen Peas\u2014California, crates, $7.00@\n8.00; Mexican, $6.00 @7.00.\nHorseradish Southern, root, per lb.,\nfancy, thick, B@loc.\nLeek Home-grown, per bunch, 12\nstalks, targe. 40c; small, 25@30c.\nLettuce Leaf Home-grown, hot\nhouse, doz. bunches, 25 30c.\nLettuce \u2014rtead \u2014iceberg, fancy, West\nern, $2.75@3.25; off-stock. $1.50@2.00.\nMushrooms \u2014Per lb.. No. 1, 1-lb. boxes,\n60@65c; buttons, 40@50c.\nOnions\u2014Tellow, sacks, per 100 lbs..\nWestern, $3.50@4.00; home-grown, $2.00\n@3.00; Spanish, per crate, ?2.00@2.25;\nValencias. 55 crate. $3.25@3.50.\nOyster Plant\u2014Per doz. bunches, SI.OO\n@l.lO.\nParsley Home-grown, dozen small\nlunches. 25 30c.\nParsnips Home-grown, bu\u201e washed.\nGive Support to All Peas\nPennsy Net Up.\nVEGETABLES.\nMILWAUKEE, TUESDAY, MARCH 29, 1927\n5\nJr\nlab\ni\nA MOST CONVENIENT WAY TO\nGROW 4 PEAS. STRETCH CHICKEN\nWIRE ON STOUT STAKES AND\nTRAIN VINES ON WIRE. THIS\nALLOWS MORE SPACE IN THE\nGARDEN AND MAKES THE WORK\nOF GATHERING THE CROP EASY.\ntical, except in the coloring of the\npeas, Alaska being blue. We now\nhave Ameer, Eureka, Electric, Mar\nket Surprise and Eight Weeks in\nthe extra early round-seeded peas\nwith larger pods and some improve\nment in quality claimed. These\npeas must be gathered while young\nto be at their best, as they lose\ntheir flavor as the peas mature.\nPicked at the proper stage, these\nextra early peas are one of the\nmost delicious of vegetables.\nBy an early planting of round\nseeded peas, to be followed in mid-\nApril in favorable seasons by a\nplanting of the early types of wrin\nkled peas, the succession of green\npeas can be readily maintained un\ntil the heat of midsummer puts an\nend to the crop.\nDistinct classes of peas have been\nevolved as to their time of matur\ning, so it is a simple matter to se\nlect earliest, second early and late\ncrops, and one planting properly se\nlected will give a succession as eas\nily as making plantings at different\ntimes of the same variety. Order\nsmooth seeded peas now for early\nplanting.\nRoads Make New\nRate Cut Plea\nWASHINGTON The Minneap\nolis, St. Paul Sault Ste. Marie\nrailway and the Minneapolis St.\nLouis railway petitioned the inter\nstate commerce commission today\nfor a reconsideration of their ap\nplications for a reduction of 6\ncents per 100 pounds on grain mov\ning from Minneapolis, St. Paul and\nDuluth to eastern seaboard points.\nThe commission disapproved the re\nduction several months ago.\nReichsbank Profit\nTakes Sharp Drop\nBERLIN\u2014The Reichsbanks\u2019 earn\nings for 1926 dropped as compared\nwith those of the previous year. The\nannual report shows a net profit\nof 22,800,000 marks, as against 42.-\n700,000 in 1925. A dividend of 10\nper cent was declared. The German\ngovernment\u2019s share of the profits\nis 4.200,000 marks, while the re\nserve gets 4,500,000.\nUpstate\u2019s Utility\nNet Shows Gain\nCHICAGO \u2014Operating revenues\nof the Lake Superior revenues of\nthe Lake Superior District Power\nCo., operating in northern Wiscon\nsin, amounted to $1,488,605 for the\nyear 1926, as compared with sl,-\n359.492 in 1925, the annual report\nissued today said.\nNet income for the year was\n$466,287, as compared with $327,-\n779 in 1925.\nCompany assets in 1926 increased\nfrom $10,490,459 to $11,478,445.\n$1.15@1.25; unwashed, 65@75c.\nPeppers\u2014Florida, crates, $5.50@6.00.\nPieplant\u2014Michigan, hot house, 5 lb.\nboxes, 90c@$1.00; California, 40 lb. boxes,\n$4.25@4.50; home-grown, per lb., 10@15c.\nPotatoes Minnesota, Michigan. Wis\nconsin, sacks, 100 lbs., white stock, on\ntrack, $2.00@2.15; Idaho, rurals, $2.75@\n3.00; russets, $3.00@3.25.\nPotatoes\u2014New\u2014Cuban, crates, $5.00\n5.50; Florida, bbls., $17.00@17.50.\nRadishes Home-grown, doz. bchs.,\nhot house, 50@60c.\nRutabagas Canadian, per 100 lbs.,\n$1.50 @1.75.\nShallots Louisiana, bblg., $9.00\n10.00.\nSpinach Texas, per bushel, $1.25\n1.50.\nString Beans Florida, hampers, wax\nor green, $5.00@6.00.\nTomatoes California, repacked. 6-\nbasket erates, $5.50@6.0Q; lugs, $2.00@\n2.50; hot house, per lb., -15@20c.\nSweet Potatoes Tennessee, hampers,\nNancy Halls, 1.75 2.00; New Jersey,\nJerseys, $2.00 @2.25; Idiana, bushels,\n$2.75 @3.00.\nTurnips Home-grown, bushels, tops\noff, 75@85c; new, Texas, bushel. $1.50@\n2.00: Louisiana, bbls., $5.00@5.50.\nWatercress\u2014Wisconsin, per bbl., $5.00\n@6.00.\nPRODUCE MARKETS.\nBeans Navies, choice, hand picked,\nper 100 lbs. (sacks included), $4.00@\n4.50; Red Kidney. $7.00@7.50; Brown\nSwedish, $6.00@6.50; Lima Beans. Cali\nfornia, $7.50 @B.OO.\nBees Wax Choice to fancy, per lb.,\nbright, 28@30c; dark. 23@25c, and\ndown to 20c.\nHoney Comb, per case, 25 1-lb. sec\ntions, fancy, white, $5.50@6.00; dark,\n$4.75@5.00; mixed sells at around $5.00.\nExtracted,- lb, white cloved. ll@12c;\namber, 9@loc.\nPeas\u2014Per 100 lbs. (new, 100-!b. sacks),\ngreen. 3.75 4.00; Scotch, $3.75@4.00;\nwhite, $3.75@4.00; marrow fats. $4.00@\n5.00; split peas, yellow, $5.75@6.00;\ngreen, $5.75@6.00.\nPop Corn\u2014Quotable per 100 lbs., ears,\n$5.00@3.5C; shelled. do. $4.00 5.00;\nbroken, poor, legs.\nTallow\u2014Prime. 9U@loc; No. 1, gelid,\n6%@7c: No. 2, s^@6c; cakes, 7\u20194@Bc:\nrough, 2U@Sc.\nWool\u2014Medium, per !b\u201e 30@S2e; low,\n?S@3oc.\nWORLD MEETING\nWILL DISCUSS\nTRADE BARRIER\nWASHINGTON Discussion of\neconomic problems of far-reaching\nimportance to the business world\nwill take place at the fourth, con\ngress of the international chamber\nof commerce in Stockholm, Sweden,\nJune 27 to July 2.\nThe complete program for the\nStockholm conference, made public\nhere today by the American section\nof the international chamber, covers\na wide range of international busi\nness subjects. The broad question\nof trade barriers is foremost on\nthe list.\nOther subjects included are com\nmercial letters of cedit, bills of ex\nchange, highway transportation, rail\ntransportation, international pro\ntection of patents and trade marks,\nair transportation, international ar\nbitration, international settlements\nand the general subject of commun\nications grouping international\nlong distance telephony and radio\nand cable rates.\nMore than 1,000 business men\nfrom the 43 member countries arc\nexpected to attend the conference.\nIt is estimated that the American\ndelegations will number more than\n200 leading business executives.\nBethlehem Employes\nReceive $444,746\nIn Seven Months\nNEW YORK\u2014Sick and disabled\nemployes and the dependents of 'de\nceased employes of Bethlehem Steel\ncorporation and its subsidiary com\npanies received $444,746.82 in the\nform of benefits under the Bethle\nhem relief plan in the first seven\nmonths of its operation ended Dec.\n31. 1926.\nThis information is detailed In\nthe first annual report of the relief\nplan issued today.\nIn the seven months there was\npaid out $229,560.55 in death bene\nfits on account of 399 deaths and\n$215,186.27 in disability benefits to\n4,447 participants on account of\nsickness or nonindustrial accidents.\nWorld Coal Output\nIn \u201926 Holds Steady\nWASHINGTON\u2014The world\u2019s pro\nduction of coal and lignite in 1926\nwas approximately 1,355,000,000\nmetric tons, practically the same as\nin 1924 and 1925, according to the\nUnited States bureau of mines.\nThe decline in the output of the\nUnited Kingdom caused by the\ngreat strike was largely offset by\nincreases in the other principal pro\nducing countries, particularly in\nGermany and the United States.\nThe output of Great Britain\ndropped from 247,000,000 to about\n127,000,000 tons, while in Germany\nthe output of bituminous coal rose\nfrom 132,729,000 to 145,362.000 tons.\nProduction in the United States to\ntaled 524,613,000 tons in 1926, com\npared to 471,781,446 tons in 1925.\nN. Y. Liberty Bonds\nNEW YORK\u2014Liberty bond prices fol\nlow: 3Us, $100.30: first 4%5, $103.11;\nsecond 4%5, $100.12; third 4%5, $101.2;\nfourth 4%5, $103.28; treasury 4%5,\n$113.20; treasury 4s, $108.6; treasury\nB^3, $105.13.\nN.Y. Stock Market Closing Prices I\nAllied Chemical\nAllis-Chalmers\nAmerican Agri. Chemical 10%\nAmerican Beet Sugar 22%\nAmerican Can 46%\nAmerican Car and F0undry....103%\nAmerican and Foreign Power.. 25\nAmerical Locomotive 110%\nAmerican Smelt, and Resin 146%\nAmerican Sugar Refining 82%\nAmerican Tel. and Tel 168\nAmerican Tobacco \u201cB\u201d 125%\nAmerican Woolen 21\nAnaconda Copper 47\nA. T. and S. F 178%\nA. T. and S. F. pfd 100%\nBaldwin Locomotive 182%\nBaltimore and Ohio 115%\nBethlehem Steel 52%\nCalifornia Packing 65%\nCalifornia Petroleum 27%\nCanadian Pacific 184%\nCase (J. I.) Thresh. Mach 158\nCerro de Pasco Copper G 2%\nChesapeake and Ohio 165\nChicago Great Western 15%\nC., M. and St. Paul 14\nC., M. and St. Paul, pfd 21%\nChicago and Northwestern 82%\nC., R. I. and Pacific 88\nChile Copper 37%\nChrysler Motor Corp 41\nColorado Fuel and Iron 59%\nConsolidation Gas 97%\nCorn Products Ref. Co 54\nDupont 216%\nElec. Power and Bight Ctfs 19%\nErie 46\nFamous Players 10\nGen. Asphalt 82%\nGen. Cigar 54\nGen. Electric 86%\nGen. Motors 182%\nGoodrich, B. F 54%\nGt. Northern pfd 86%\nGt. North. Ore Ctfs 20%\nGreene Cananca 38%\nHudson Motor 69%\n111. Central 126%\nIndian Ref 9%\nInspiration Copper 20\nInt. Harvester 155%\nInt. Paper 56%\nK. C. Southern 51\nKennecott Copper 62%\nKresge S. S 51\nLehigh Valley 117%\nLou. and Nash 134%\nALFALFA GREAT CREAM PRODUCER\nALFALFA MAKES MOST CREAM PER ACRE\nj j O*\nJU J4A j\nn McMinn\nmw.; |92 Iba. Purchased. U 2/ BuSerfet\nOmAratf CiAaFnAl^a\u00dfsboT\" Concentrate# i Good Dairy Cow\nTlH\u00bbT\u00bbrt CojaN j e*TS k S CM* 400 CMK*)\nma\u00bb A;\nflfl\n240 lUhrcW 60\nAlfalfa not only exceeds dll\nother hay crops in yield and\nquality, but its use in a well\nbalanced dairy cow ration\nmakes it possible for the farm\ner to get more pounds of but\nterfat per acre of crops grown\nfor feed, states the Blue Val\nley Creamery institute.\nThe farmer who grows al\n'falfa in combination with\n\u2018SHORT LINE'S'\nSALE BARRED\nNEW YORK The interstate\ncommerce commission yesterday\nwas advised by its examiner to re\nfuse the Chesapeake Ohio rail\nroad authority to purchase the 11-\nmile line in West Virginia of the\nGreenbriar Eastern road at a\nprice of approximately $1,400,000.\n\u201cThe attitude of the Chesapeake\nOhio officials in refusing to the\nparties claiming title to a portion\nof the stock access to contracts en\ntered into for the purchase of that\nstocks is open to criticism,\u201d the ex\naminer, T. F. Sulivan, declared.\n\u201cThe disposition utterly to disre\ngard the right of minority stock\nholders is evidenced by the terms\nof the contract. The attitude of\nthe Chesapeake Ohio officials to\nward the Gauley Coal Co. (a minor\nity holder of Greenbriar stock) can\nhardly be classed as creditable.\u201d\nThe price for the line finally agreed\nto, the examiner said, \u201cappears to\nbe excessive in the light of the facts\nof record.\u201d\nlowa Bank Bills\nUp Before Houses\nDES MOINES, la\u2014The Lovrien\nguaranty bill, which includes a pro\nvision for a state-wide clearing\nhouse, conies up for consideration\ntoday.\nThe proposals of rhe lowa Bank\ners\u2019 Assn, is in turn to form the\nbasis for a committee bill to be in\ntroduced this week. This measure\nfixes minimum capitalization for\nbanks and, like the Lovrien bill,\nwould establish a state-wide clear\ning house system.\nThe bankers\u2019 association, however,\nopposed guaranty in any form. A\nmeasure sponsored by the governor\nwould compel bank stockholders to\ndeposit, with the state, securities\nequal to 100 per cent of their bank\nstock holdings.\nMonday\nClose.\nMaryland Oil 50\nMonday\nClose.\nMiami Copper 152\nMo. Kan. and Tex 39^\nMo. Pacific 52\nMonty Ward 65%\nNational Biscuit Co 113\nNational Lead 192\nNevada Cons. Copper 14%\nN. Y. Central 145%\nN. Y\u201e N. H. Hartford 50%\nNorthern Pacific 86%\nPacific Oil 1%\nPan. Amn. Pet. Transport.... 63\nPenn. Railroad 59%\nPure Oil Co 28%\nPeople\u2019s Gas 131%\nRay Cons. Copper 15%\nReading 110\nReplogle Steel 11\nRep. Iron Steel 71%\nRoyal Dutch 50%\nSears, Roebuck Co 54%\nShell Union Oil 29\nSinclair Consolidated Oil 18\nSouthern Pacific 112%\nSouthern Raliroad 121%\nStandard Oil of Calif 56%\nStandard Oil of N. J 37%\nStudebaker Co 53\nTennessee Copper and Chern.... 11\nTexas and Pacific 64%\nTimken Roller Bearing 85%\nTobacco Products 103%\nTranscontinental Oil 4%\nUnion Oil of Calif 44%\nUnion Pacific 170%\nU. S. Rubber Co 62%\nU. S. Steel Corp 165%\nU. S. Steel, pfd 130%\nVanadium Corp 50%\nWabash 71%\nWabash, pfd. \u201cA\u201d 95\nWestinghouse E. and M 76%\nWillys-Overland 21%\nYellow Truck and Coach 25%\nMILWAUKEE HAY MARKST.\nNo. 1 timothy, 518.00 019.00; No. 2\ntimothy, $16.00@18.00; No. 3 timothy.\n$13.00 16.00; No. 1 mixed, $18.00; No. 2\nclover mixed, $16.00; sample hay, SIO.OO\n@13.00; marsh feeding, $ll.OO @12.00;\npacking, SIO.OO @10.50; rye straw, SIO.OO\n@10.50; oat straw. $10.00@10.50.\nMILWAUKEE CAR RECEIPTS.\nMil. N. W. Soo Total\nWheat 1 1\nCorn 13 7 20\nOats 4 17 21\nBarley 10 17 3 29\nRyo 1 2 3\nTotals 2* 44 3 74\nPAGE TWELVE\ncorn and oats reduces his re\nquirements for purchased con\ncentrates to balance his ration\nproperly.\nA suitable ration containing\nalfalfa hay can be made up of\n12 pounds alfalfa hhy, 36\npounds of corn silage, four\npounds of ground corn, two\npounds of ground oats, and\none pound of linseed oil meal.\nEarly Spring Seen\nAs Boon to lowa\nCrops for 1927\nDES MOINES\u2014The first crop\nbulletin of the season released by\nC. D. Reed, director of the lowa\nweather and crop service, states\nthat recent warm, sunny weather\nwas a great benefit to young pigs\nand lambs.\nWinter wheat and meadows bene\nfited by copious rains. Some oats\nand spring wheat was sown. Fruit\nbuds in southern sections of the\nstate are opening two weeks ahead\nof average season. There is consid\nerable plowing and clearing away\nof corn stalks.\nWinter wheat came through in\nfine condition. Dairy animals are in\nprime condition and milk flow un\nusually good. No hog cholera has\nbeen reported and \u201cflu\u201d has prac\ntically subsided. Farmers report\ntests of seed corn satisfactory.\nClover and alfalfa came through\nthe winter in good condition.\nChicago Livestock\nCHICAGO Cattle\u2014Receipts, 20,000;\nall classes steady; better grade fed\nsteers with weight, strong in most in\nstances, active; largely of steer run;\nkilling quality good to choice; mostly\ngood; bulk fed steers and yearlings, $9.50\n@12.00; best yearlings, $12.00; strictly\nchoice heavies around $13.50; Stockers\nand feeders again very scarce, firm at\n$8.50@9.00 mostly; light vealers to big\npackers, $9.00 @10.00; outsider# $ll.OO\n13.00.\nSheep\u2014Receipts, 18,000; fat iambs ac\ntive; early sales 25 50c higher than\nFriday; good to choice handy and me\ndiumweight wooled lambs upward to\n$16.50; early bulk desirable offerings,\n$15.75@16.25; good heavy lambs upward\nto $15.75; good to choice mediumweight\nclipped lambs, $14.50; choice handy\nweights held above $14.85; culls, $12.00@\n13.00; sheep strong; good to choice fat\newes, $10.00; choice clipped ewes up to\n$9.00; feeding and shearing lambs scarce,\nstrong.\nNew York Produce\nNEW YORK\u2014Flour, steady and un\nchanged. Pork, dull; mess, $37.50. Lard,\neasy; midwest spot, $12.95 @13.05. Sugar,\nraw, quiet; spot, 96 test, delivered duty\npaid, $4.68@4.74; refined, dull; granu\nlated, $5.85@6.20. Coffee, Rio No. 7 on\nspot, 16@16%c; Santos No. 4, 18@18%c.\nTallow, quiet; special to extra, 7%@\n7%c. Hay, dull; No. 1, $1.30; No. 3,\n$1.00; clover, $1.10@1.25. Dressed poul\ntry, quiet; turkeys, 35@48c; chickens,\n20@38c; broilers, 50@60c; capons, 28@\n45c; fowls. 17@33c; duckp, 20@25c; Long\nIslands, 22 26c. Live poultry, firm;\ngeese, 11 17c; ducks, 19@30c; fowls,\n29@30c; turkeys, 35@40c; roosters, 18c;\nchickens, 22@32c; capons, 26@35c;\nbroilers, 35 55c. Cheese, dull; state\nwhole milk, s fancy to specials, 27@28c;\nYoung Americas, 25@27%c. Sweet pota\ntoes, Jersey, basket, 50c@52.25; southern,\nbasket, $1.50. Butter, firmer, receipts,\n6,14 5; creamery extra, 51 %c; special\nmarket, 52@52%c. Eggs, quiet; receipts,\n25,083; nearby white fancy, 33@34c;\nnearby state whites, 27@32c; fresh firsts,\n25%@26c; Pacific coast, 29@35c; west\nern whites, 26@30c; nearby browns, 30\n@32c.\nPRIMARY GRAIN MOVEMENT.\nP